  "text": "The syndrome of autoimmune polyendocrinopathy-candidiasis-ectodermal dystrophy (APECED), or autoimmune polyendocrine syndrome 1 (APS-1), is a rare AR PID characterized by CMC that is often its earliest manifestation, in addition to multiple autoimmune endocrinopathies, hypoparathyroidism, and adrenal insufficiency. The genetic cause of APECED are mutations in the autoimmune regulator (AIRE) gene [CITATION_1] . Loss of function of AIRE in patients leads to impaired central T cell tolerance, with the generation of neutralizing autoantibodies against IL-17A, IL-17F, and/or IL-22, which might account for CMC [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . These immunodeficiencies collectively point to a fundamental role for IL-17 signaling in the protection against mucosal Candida infection in humans.",
